The paper deals with complexity classes and algorithms for solving problems with unique solutions, which are fundamental topics in theoretical computer science. The use of line-following algorithms and potential functions suggests a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG), while the study of fixpoints and linear complementarity problems points towards computational complexity (cs.CC) and optimization (cs.DS). The mention of parity games, mean-payoff games, and stochastic games also suggests a connection to game theory (cs.GT) and reinforcement learning (cs.LG).
